Two members of ETA were arrested transporting explosives to Madrid before the 2004 bombings and received 22-year jail sentences each.
Accused of placing the bombs, Zougam was linked to Al-Qaeda and arrested for his involvement.
The trial of 29 suspects, including Ahmed, began, with tight security measures in place.
Ahmed denied all accusations, claiming no recognition of the charges.
The attacks, inspired by Al-Qaeda, killed 191 people and injured over 1,800.
The trial involves extensive evidence and witnesses, shedding light on the tragic events of March 11, 2004.
